Flexbox, short for Flexible Box Module, is a layout model in CSS that allows you to easily design a flexible responsive layout structure without using float or positioning.

In a flex container, you can align elements horizontally and vertically, dictate the order of elements, and control their sizes to fill available space or shrink to prevent overflow.

Here's a basic example of how to use Flexbox:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
}

.item {
  flex-grow: 1;
}
```

In this example, `.container` is a flex container, and any direct children of `.container` are flex items. `justify-content: space-between;` aligns the items along the horizontal line and adds space between them. `flex-grow: 1;` makes the items grow to fill the container if there's extra space.

Flexbox is a powerful tool for creating responsive layouts, and it's supported in all modern browsers. For a more detailed guide, you can check out the [MDN Web Docs](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Flexible_Box_Layout/Basic_Concepts_of_Flexbox).

Yes, Flexbox is a great choice for creating a layout with different sections. Each section can be a standalone component, and you can use Flexbox to control the layout of these components.

For example, if you want to create a layout with a header, a main content area, and a footer, you could structure your components like this:

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div className="app">
      <Header />
      <MainContent />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

And use Flexbox in your CSS to control the layout:

```css
.app {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  height: 100vh;
}

.header {
  /* Styles for header */
}

.main-content {
  flex-grow: 1;
  /* This will make the main content area take up any remaining space */
}

.footer {
  /* Styles for footer */
}
```

This is a very basic example. Flexbox is very flexible and can be used to create more complex layouts as well. For example, you could use nested flex containers to create a layout with a sidebar and a main content area, or a grid of cards.

