The CSS rule you've written will apply the styles to any element with the class `pi` that is a child of an element with the class `red-icon`. 

If your button's icon is not a child element but is instead being applied directly to the button element with class `red-icon`, the rule won't apply because there's no child with class `pi`.

If you want to apply the styles to the button itself, you should remove the space in your selector:

```css
.red-icon.pi {
    color: red;
    background-color: white;
}
```

This rule will apply the styles to any element that has both the `red-icon` and `pi` classes. 

However, if the `pi` class is being added dynamically (for example, by a library you're using), and you don't have control over the class names being applied to the button, you might not be able to use this approach. In that case, you would need to find a different way to select the button, such as using a different class name or a different type of selector.

In CSS, an element will inherit the background color of its parent by default if no background color is explicitly set for the element. However, if a background color is set for the element, it will override the parent's background color.

If you want an element to always use the background color of its parent, even if a background color is set for the element, you can use the `inherit` value for the `background-color` property. Here's how you can do it:

```css
.child-element {
  background-color: inherit;
}
```

In this code, `background-color: inherit;` sets the background color of the `.child-element` to the background color of its parent element.

Please replace `.child-element` with the actual selector you want to use to select the element.

Yes, you can use the context manager to provide the WebSocket connection to different components, and each component can then set up its own message handler. 

In your `LogDisplay` component, you're already doing this. You're getting the WebSocket connection from the context, and then in the `useEffect` hook, you're setting up a message handler specifically for this component:

```javascript
const handleMessage = (event) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
  if (data.type == "log") {
    setLogs((prevLogs) => [...prevLogs, data.message]);
  }
};

ws.addEventListener("message", handleMessage);
```

This `handleMessage` function is specific to the `LogDisplay` component. Other components that also get the WebSocket connection from the context can set up their own message handlers in a similar way.

This is one of the benefits of using context to provide the WebSocket connection. It allows each component to interact with the WebSocket in a way that's appropriate for that component, while still ensuring that there's only one WebSocket connection for the entire application.
